In <1993Jun23.155545.28671@cc.ic.ac.uk> pjc@cc.ic.ac.uk (Peter Churchyard) writes:


>Not being a US/Canada citizen, if I have software that does encryption
>and email it to another person also not in US/Canada and it happens to
>get routed via an email relay in the US, are the export laws being broken
>in the US?

Probably.  Also patent laws, if the encryption procedure is covered by a US
patent.  As far as I know, no prosecutions have ever been made.

>Unless you are actually using PEM or PGP to send email, can they legally
>prove that you are the one who sent email? Can it stand up in court even if
>you ARE using PEM or PGP.

Who knows?

>Are the export restriction laws more like speed limits that most people 
>ignore at various times or like murder laws that most people feel should
>be obeyed?

Most people aren't aware of them.
